Absolutely, I can help you set up a custom DDEV-based Docker environment for a Drupal 10 site.

Below is a step-by-step guide to get you started, tailored for Drupal 10.1.6 and using best practices:

✅ Prerequisites

Make sure the following are installed on your machine:

  • Docker Desktop

  • DDEV

  • Git (optional, but useful)

🔧 Step-by-Step: Custom DDEV Setup for Drupal 10

1. Create a Project Directory

bash
mkdir my-drupal10-site && cd my-drupal10-site

2. Initialize DDEV Project

bash
ddev config --project-type=drupal10 --docroot=web --create-docroot

  • --project-type=drupal10 ensures compatibility with Drupal 10.

  • --docroot=web follows the recommended Drupal Composer project structure.

  • --create-docroot creates the web directory automatically.

3. Install Drupal via Composer

Use the official drupal/recommended-project:

bash
ddev composer create "drupal/recommended-project:^10.1" --no-install
ddev composer install

This sets up a Composer-based Drupal 10.1.x codebase with proper directory structure.

4. Start DDEV Environment

bash
ddev start

This will spin up the containers and generate the .ddev directory with your config.

5. Install Drupal via Drush

Run the site install:

bash
ddev composer require drush/drush
ddev drush site:install standard \
  --account-name=admin \
  --account-pass=admin \
  --db-url=mysql://db:db@db/db \
  --site-name="My Drupal 10 Site"

💡 You can change the site name, admin credentials, etc.

6. Visit Your Site

Your new Drupal 10 site will be available at:

bash
ddev launch

🧩 Optional: Custom Configuration & Add-ons

➕ Enable Xdebug

bash
ddev xdebug enable

🔍 Enable Webgrind (Profiling)

bash
ddev webgrind

🌐 Custom URLs / Hostnames

Edit .ddev/config.yaml:

yaml
additional_hostnames:
  - custom.local

Then run:

bash
ddev restart

🛠 Customization Notes

  • PHP version: DDEV defaults to PHP 8.1, but you can change it:

yaml
php_version: "8.1"

(inside .ddev/config.yaml)

  • Custom Docker services: You can add custom services via .ddev/docker-compose.*.yaml.

✅ Final Directory Structure

Your final project will look like:

pgsql
my-drupal10-site/
├── .ddev/
├── vendor/
├── web/
│   ├── core/
│   ├── modules/
│   └── index.php
├── composer.json
└── composer.lock

  • Add custom modules/themes?

  • Connect to Tugboat, Pantheon, or Acquia later?

  • Integrate CI/CD via GitHub Actions or CircleCI?

Yes, exactly — you'll need Docker Desktop running the entire time you're working with DDEV.

🐳 Why Docker Needs to Be Running

DDEV is built on top of Docker. When you run:

bash
ddev start

…it uses Docker to spin up containers for:

  • Web server (Apache/Nginx + PHP 8.1 or 8.2)

  • Database (usually MariaDB or MySQL)

  • Optional services like MailHog, Redis, Xdebug, etc.

If Docker isn't running, you'll get errors like:

pgsql
Failed to start projectname: Docker is not running

✅ Before You Start

Make sure Docker is running — you should see the whale icon in your Mac’s menu bar, like this:

🐳 | Docker Desktop running

If it’s not running, open it via Spotlight or Launchpad:

bash
⌘ + Space → type "Docker" → Enter

Then wait for it to say "Docker is running" before using DDEV.

Let me know if you want me to check your .ddev/config.yaml or need help setting a custom PHP version, like PHP 8.1 or 8.2.

Then you're inside the container (Linux shell), and you can run normal CLI stuff like:

But 95% of the time, you can and should stay in your Mac terminal and just prefix commands with ddev.

✅ Step 5: Sync Files from Acquia Dev Environment

In Drupal, user-uploaded files (images, PDFs, media, etc.) are stored in the sites/default/files/ directory. This directory is not included in the database or tracked by Git, so after importing the database, your local site may appear broken (missing images, media, etc.) unless you also sync the files.

🔁 Step 5: Sync Public Files

Option A: Using Drush rsync (if Drush alias is working)

bash
ddev drush rsync @tactis.dev:%files/ sites/default/files

This command copies all files from Acquia Dev’s file system into your local DDEV site's sites/default/files/.

Option B: Using Acquia CLI

If you prefer Acquia CLI and it's configured:

bash
acli pull:files tactis.dev --yes

This does essentially the same thing — pulls down the public files directory from Acquia Dev to your local project.

📌 Why This Matters

Without this step:

  • Images will be broken (e.g., /sites/default/files/images/foo.jpg won’t exist).

  • Media entities may reference missing files.

  • Migration code that touches the file system may fail.

📝 Notes

  • This only covers public files (sites/default/files).

  • If your project uses private files, you may need to sync those separately (sites/default/private or ../private/ depending on your settings).

  • This won’t affect Composer or code — just file assets.

Let me know if the Drush alias @tactis.dev isn’t working and I’ll help you recreate it — or if you’d prefer to manually download files from Acquia Cloud UI.
